# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bornean-orangutan
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bornean-orangutan/american-society-of-mammalogists] The **American Society of Mammalogists** (**ASM**) was founded in 1919 to encourage the study of mammals.
[src:bornean-orangutan/american-society-of-mammalogists] There are over 4,500 members, primarily professional scientists who emphasize the importance of public policy and education.
[src:bornean-orangutan/american-society-of-mammalogists] There are several ASM meetings held each year, and the society manages several publications such as the *Journal of Mammalogy*, *Special Publications*, *Mammalian Species*, and *Society Pamphlets*.
[src:bornean-orangutan/american-society-of-mammalogists] The best known of these is the *Journal of Mammalogy*.
[src:bornean-orangutan/american-society-of-mammalogists] The ASM also maintains *The Mammal Image Library* which contains more than 1,300 mammal slides.
[src:bornean-orangutan/american-society-of-mammalogists] A president, vice president, recording secretary, secretary-treasurer, and journal editor are all elected by the members to be officers of the society.
[src:bornean-orangutan/american-society-of-mammalogists] In addition, ASM is composed of thirty one committees, including the Animal Care and Use Committee, the Conservation Awards Committee, the International Relations Committee, and the Publications Committee.
[src:bornean-orangutan/american-society-of-mammalogists] It also provides numerous grants and awards for research and studies on mammals.
[src:bornean-orangutan/american-society-of-mammalogists] These awards can go to both scientists and students.
[src:bornean-orangutan/american-society-of-mammalogists] The ASM also lists employment opportunities for their members.
[src:bornean-orangutan/american-society-of-mammalogists] Milo Herrick Spaulding was a charter member.
[src:bornean-orangutan/american-society-of-mammalogists] Since 2018, the American Society of Mammalogists has maintained the Mammal Diversity Database, an online checklist of mammal species.
[src:bornean-orangutan/american-society-of-mammalogists] The database is maintained by the ASM Biodiversity Committee and "aims to provide a continuously updated listing of the world's mammal species and higher taxa." The latest update (version 2.2) was released on June 13, 2025, and lists 6,815 species placed in 1,359 genera, 167 families and 27 orders.
[src:bornean-orangutan/american-society-of-mammalogists] A list of world mammalogical societies associated with or that publish in the ASM.
[src:bornean-orangutan/american-society-of-mammalogists] By 2017, the ASM had 865 non-US members from 88 countries.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Often, these structures incorporate sophisticated features such as temperature regulation, traps, bait, ventilation, special-purpose chambers and many other features.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] They may be created by individuals or complex societies of social animals with different forms carrying out specialized roles.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] The process of building such structures may involve learning and communication, and in some cases, even aesthetics.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Tool use may also be involved in building structures by animals.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Building behaviour is common in many non-human mammals, birds, insects and arachnids.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] It is also seen in a few species of fish, reptiles, amphibians, molluscs, urochordates, crustaceans, annelids and some other arthropods.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] It is virtually absent from all the other animal phyla.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Animals primarily build habitat for protection from extreme temperatures and from predation.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Constructed structures raise physical problems which need to be resolved, such as humidity control or ventilation, which increases the complexity of the structure.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Over time, through evolution, animals use shelters for other purposes such as reproduction, food storage, etc.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Predators are attracted to animal-built structures either by the prey or its offspring, or the stored caches of food.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Structures built by animals may provide protection from predators through avoiding detection, by means such as camouflage and concealment, or through prevention of invasion, once predators have located the hideout or prey, or a combination of both.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] As a last resort, structures may provide means of escape.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Among the structures created by animals to prevent predation are those of the paper wasps, *Polistes chinensis antennalis.* The nests of these wasps contain “defensive structures”, which are formations built onto or inside of the nest to prevent predation.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] New nests are formed in the spring by young queens, as worker wasps have not hatched at this time.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] While these worker wasps are growing in the nest, they are vulnerable to predators who might rip open the nest to eat the larva.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] One method the queens use to prevent this is covering the developing pupae in pulp, which acts as a reinforcer and makes it more difficult from predators to break open the pupae.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] This pulp is a mixture of plant matter and liquids from the mouth of the queen wasp.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] While there are costs associated with using pulp, such as requiring time and energy to collect materials and hindering the emergence of the worker wasps from the cocoon, it does lower the risk of predation.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Nests in areas with higher predation rates have been found to contain more pulp on these cocoons than nests in low predation areas.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Animals use the techniques of crypsis or camouflage, concealment, and mimicry, for avoiding detection.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Some species of birds will use materials foraged from nature to camouflage their nests and prevent their offspring from being hunted.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Crypsis works by blending the structure with its background.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] The use of lichen flakes as an outer covering of nests by birds, as in the case of the paradise flycatcher (*Terpsiphone paradisei*) have been considered by some authors to be a case of crypsis through "branch-matching" and as a case of disruptive camouflage by the British ethologist, M.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Hansell, where the lichen flakes are thought to resemble small patches of light seen through as in the case of insubstantial objects of insufficient importance to receive a predator's interest.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Ground-nesting birds which rely on crypsis for concealment have nests made from local materials which blend in with the background, the eggs and young too are cryptic; whereas birds which do not use crypsis for hiding their nests may not have cryptic eggs or young.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] In a case apparently of masquerade, the red-faced spinetail *Cranioleuca erythrops* places bits of grass and other material loosely streaming both above and below the nest chamber to break the shape of the nest and to cause it to resemble random debris without any underlying structure.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Temperature extremes harm animals irrespective of whether they are endothermic or ectothermic.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] In endothermic animals, construction of shelters, coupled with behavioural patterns, reduces the quantity and energy cost of thermoregulation, as in the case of the Arctic ground squirrels.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] In ectothermic animals, moderation of temperature, along with architectural modifications to absorb, trap or dissipate energy, maximises the rate of development, as in the case of the communal silk nests of the small eggar moth *Eriogaster lanestris*.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] The primary sources of energy for an animal are the sun and its metabolism.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] The dynamics of heat in animal shelters is influenced by the construction material which may act as a barrier, as a heat sink or to dissipate heat.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] The cocoons of insect are a case in point.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] An interesting example is the case of silk caps which cover the pupal cells of the Oriental hornet *Vespa orientalis*.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Firstly, the silk insulates the pupa from the air outside the cell, and secondly, it acts as a thermostatic regulator.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] By virtue of its thermoelectric properties, the silk stores excess daytime heat in the form of electric charge which it releases in the form of an electric current when the temperature falls resulting in heating.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Cooling is aided by evaporation of excess water from the pupal cells.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] When the ambient temperature drops, the silk absorbs moisture and restores the moisture content by spreading water through all parts of its cocoon.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Internal architectural devices, such as walls may block convection or the construction of air flow systems may cool the nest or habitat.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Trap-building is a method used to catch prey instead of active hunting.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Animals that snare prey will construct a trap and then wait nearby until an organism is caught.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] This is observed in web-building spiders, who weave elaborate webs of sticky spider silk that entangle prey.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Spiders increase the size of their webs when prey are scarce, and can add extra ornamental pieces to their web in order to attract more prey.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Traps can allow organisms to capture larger prey, provide protection from predators, or serve as an area for mating, as seen with spiders.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Another method of trap creation is used by the antlion (*Myrmeleon crudelis*) larva.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] These larva prey on small arthropods, such as ants.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] The larva dig pits into fine-particle soil to capture their prey, which fall into the holes and are often unable to climb out.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] The antlions may alter these pits based on prey availability.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] In areas with less available prey, antlions will make wider holes to increase the chance of catching an insect.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] If prey are able to climb out of the hole, antlions will increase the depth of the hole.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Animal structures can serve as a means of communication with other organisms.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Animals may construct to attract mates, as seen in species of male fiddler crabs.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] These crabs may form "pillars" or "hoods" out of sand and mud to gain the attention of nearby females.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Bowerbirds (*Ptilonorhynchus violaceus)* also create display structures to attract mates.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] During the mating season, male Bowerbirds will collect twigs and colourful objects to create structures known as "bowers", which attract the attention of females.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Bowers that are more colourful and well constructed are more attractive to female bowerbirds, as the quality of the constructed bowers reflects the quality of the male bird.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Army ants (*Eciton hamatum*) form "living bridges" to assist in transportation.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Army ant colonies may move locations each day in search of food.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] These bridges provide a path over obstacles and allow for the ants to search for food at an increased speed.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] The bridges are constructed when the ants join their bodies together, and can vary in size and shape depending on the situation the ants face.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Ants are confined to their position when they are forming these bridges, preventing them from moving.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] The bridges are broken apart when they are no longer needed.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Materials used by animals in building structures need to not only be suitable for the kind of structure to be built but also to be manipulable by the animals.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] These materials may be organic in nature or mineral.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] They may also be categorised as "collected material" and "self-secreted material".
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Some animals collect materials with plastic properties which are used to construct and shape the nest.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] These include resin collected by stingless bees, mud collected by swallows and silk collected by hummingbirds.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Some materials in nature act as ready made "building blocks" to the animals in question, such as feathers and leaf petioles for some birds and animal hair for the chaffinch.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Caddisfly larvae use stone pieces and also cut sections from green leaves for use in construction.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] The stone pieces are selected as per their size and shape from a large variety.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] In the case of leaf sections, these are cut and shaped to required size.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Similarly bagworms cut and shape thorns or twigs to form their case.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Some sphecid wasps collect mud and blend them with water to construct free standing nests of mud.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Paper wasp queens build with paper pulp which they prepare by rasping wood with their jaws and mixing with saliva, a case of collecting, processing and blending raw materials.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] An animal builder may collect a variety of materials and use them in complex ways to form useful habitat.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] The nest of the long-tailed tit, *Aegithalos caudatus*, is constructed from four materials – lichen, feathers, spider egg cocoons and moss, over 6000 pieces in all for a typical nest.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] The nest is a flexible sac with a small, round entrance on top, suspended low in a gorse or bramble bush.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] The structural stability of the nest is provided by a mesh of moss and spider silk.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] The tiny leaves of the moss act as hooks and the spider silk of egg cocoons provides the loops; thus forming a natural form of velcro.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] The tit lines the outside with hundreds of flakes of pale lichens – this provides camouflage.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Inside, it lines the nest with more than 2000 feathers to insulate the nest.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Birds form the majority of the group of animals which collect building material of animal origin.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] They collect animal fur and feathers of other species of birds to line their nests.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Almost 56% of all families of passerine birds have species which utilise spider silk.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Most birds use spider silk as in the case of the long-tailed tit, previously discussed; however the little spiderhunter (*Arachnothera longirostra*) of Asian tropical forests uses spider silk differently.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] It constructs a nest of plant strips which it suspends below a large leaf using spider silk for about a 150 or so of "pop-rivets".
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Flowering plants provide a variety of resources – twigs, leaves, petioles, roots, flowers and seeds.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Basal plants, such as lichens, mosses and ferns also find use in structures built by animals.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] The leaves of grasses and palms being elongate and parallel-veined are very commonly used for building.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] These, along with palm fibers and horse-hair fern are used to build hanging baskets.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Wooden twigs form the greater proportion of materials used in the nests of large birds.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Plants and trees not only provide resources but also sites.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Branches provide support in the form of cantilevered beams while leaves and green twigs provide flexible but strong supports.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Structures formed from plant material include beaver dams, which are constructed by foraged branches and sticks.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] The dam is a wall of sticks constructed on a moving water source, which forces the water to collect in one area and to stop flowing.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Beavers begin to build a dam in an area where rocks and other debris slow the flow of the water.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] The beavers then form a small platform of sticks stretching across the water source.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] More sticks and branches are added to build the dam up over time.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] The structure in the center of the dam, known as the lodge, serves as a home for the beavers and protects them from predators.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] The primary reason behind the construction of beaver dams is to surround the lodge with deep water, which protects the beaver from land-dwelling predators.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] The entrance of the dam is underwater to prevent predators such as bears and wolves from entering, and the sticks at the top of the lodge are not packed tightly, which allows air into the structure.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Mud is used by a few species of a wide variety of families including wasps and birds.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Mud is plastic when wet and provides compressive strength when dried.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Amongst birds, 5% of all birds use mud and stones in their nest for toughness and compressive strength.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Males in some species of crab will construct structures out of mud to attract mates and avoid predators.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] *Uca musica*, also known as fiddler crabs, will build short, wide “hoods” out of sand.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Another species of crab, *Uca beebei,* will build tall, thin pillars out of mud.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] These structures attract female crabs to male crab burrows and provide a hiding place for both males and females when predators are nearby.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Beavers will often seal their dams and lodges with mud for extra support.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] The majority of self-secreted materials are produced by insects and selection acts on this characteristic of production of self-secreting materials and increases the fitness of the animal.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Self-secreted materials may be processed in some cases.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] In cribellate spiders, silk produced by the spider are reworked in the cribellum to form fine sticky strands used for capturing prey.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Not all self-secreted materials are developed specifically for that purpose.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] For example, bird feathers are used for lining and insulation, a typical example being that of the female common eider duck (*Somateria mollissima*), which produces down feathers for lining its nest.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Cocoons are another type of structure formed to protect the organism from predation.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] In order to transform from a larva into a butterfly or moth, a caterpillar must undergo drastic changes in its body.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] These changes require significant amounts of energy and occur over long periods of time, making a caterpillar very vulnerable to predation.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] To overcome this, caterpillars will produce silk to form a cocoon or pupa, a structure in which the caterpillar will reside while pupating to lower its risk of predation.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Some species of caterpillar, such as the silkworm (*Bombyx mori*) are able to spin multiple cocoons in the event that one gets destroyed.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Other caterpillars will even form defensive structures to accompany their pupas.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] The *Aethria carnicauda* caterpillar uses the hairs that cover its body as a defensive mechanism against predators.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] When it is time to form a cocoon, the caterpillar rips the hairs off of its body and places them around the pupating site.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] This creates a series of defensive walls to protect the vulnerable caterpillar while resides in its cocoon.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-architecture] Recently, some researchers have argued that the structures built by animals affect the evolution of the constructor, a phenomenon known as niche construction.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-diversity-web] The **Animal Diversity Web** (**ADW**) is a non-profit group that hosts an online database site that collects natural history, classification, species characteristics, conservation biology, and distribution information on species of animals.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-diversity-web] The website includes photographs, sound clips, and a virtual museum.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-diversity-web] The local, relational database is written and maintained by staff and student contributors from the University of Michigan.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-diversity-web] It can be accessed through the web and mobile apps.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-diversity-web] It offers resources for schoolteachers ("K–12 instructors"), and functions as a virtual museum containing mostly mammals and a collection of skulls that can be virtually handled.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-diversity-web] The ADW was created in 1995 by Philip Myers, a former biology professor at the University of Michigan.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-diversity-web] As of June 2022, the site contained records for approximately 2,150 animal species, represented by 11,500 images and 725 sounds.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-diversity-web] The ADW has over 250 accounts of higher taxonomic groups.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-diversity-web] Most of the contributors to the website are undergraduate students.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-diversity-web] ADW has collaborated with 30 colleges and universities across the United States.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-diversity-web] The undergraduate students often submit reports on species as part of their course requirements.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-diversity-web] Each account is edited by both the professors and the staff at the ADW.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal-diversity-web] As of November 2017, the Animal Diversity Web had 3,675 contributors.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The animal kingdom is divided into five major clades, namely Porifera, Ctenophora, Placozoa, Cnidaria and Bilateria.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The much smaller basal phylum Xenacoelomorpha have an uncertain position within Bilateria.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Animals first appeared in the fossil record in the late Cryogenian period and diversified in the subsequent Ediacaran period in what is known as the Avalon explosion.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Nearly all modern animal phyla first appeared in the fossil record as marine species during the Cambrian explosion, which began around 539 million years ago (Mya), and most classes during the Ordovician radiation 485.4 Mya.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Common to all living animals, 6,331 groups of genes have been identified that may have arisen from a single common ancestor that lived about 650 Mya during the Cryogenian period.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Historically, Aristotle divided animals into those with blood and those without.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Carl Linnaeus created the first hierarchical biological classification for animals in 1758 with his *Systema Naturae*, which Jean-Baptiste Lamarck expanded into 14 phyla by 1809.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] In 1874, Ernst Haeckel divided the animal kingdom into the multicellular **Metazoa** (now synonymous with Animalia) and the Protozoa, single-celled organisms no longer considered animals.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] In modern times, the biological classification of animals relies on advanced techniques, such as molecular phylogenetics, which are effective at demonstrating the evolutionary relationships between taxa.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Humans make use of many other animal species for food (including meat, eggs, and dairy products), for materials (such as leather, fur, and wool), as pets and as working animals for transportation, and services.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Dogs, the first domesticated animal, have been used in hunting, in security and in warfare, as have horses, pigeons and birds of prey; while other terrestrial and aquatic animals are hunted for sports, trophies or profits.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Non-human animals are also an important cultural element of human evolution, having appeared in cave arts and totems since the earliest times, and are frequently featured in mythology, religion, arts, literature, heraldry, politics, and sports.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The word *animal* comes from the Latin noun *animal* of the same meaning, which is itself derived from Latin *animalis* 'having breath or soul'.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The biological definition includes all members of the kingdom Animalia.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] In colloquial usage, the term *animal* is often used to refer only to nonhuman animals.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The term *metazoa* is derived from Ancient Greek μετα *meta* 'after' (in biology, the prefix *meta-* stands for 'later') and ζῷᾰ *zōia* 'animals', plural of ζῷον *zōion* 'animal'.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] A **metazoan** is any member of the group *Metazoa*.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Animals have several characteristics that they share with other living things.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Animals are eukaryotic, multicellular, and aerobic, as are plants and fungi.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Unlike plants and algae, which produce their own food, animals cannot produce their own food, a feature they share with fungi.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Animals ingest organic material and digest it internally.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Typically, there is an internal digestive chamber with either one opening (in Ctenophora, Cnidaria, and flatworms) or two openings (in most bilaterians).
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Animal development is controlled by Hox genes, which signal the times and places to develop structures such as body segments and limbs.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] During development, the animal extracellular matrix forms a relatively flexible framework upon which cells can move about and be reorganised into specialised tissues and organs, making the formation of complex structures possible, and allowing cells to be differentiated.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The extracellular matrix may be calcified, forming structures such as shells, bones, and spicules.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] In contrast, the cells of other multicellular organisms (primarily algae, plants, and fungi) are held in place by cell walls, and so develop by progressive growth.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Nearly all animals make use of some form of sexual reproduction.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] They produce haploid gametes by meiosis; the smaller, motile gametes are spermatozoa and the larger, non-motile gametes are ova.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] These fuse to form zygotes, which develop via mitosis into a hollow sphere, called a blastula.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] In sponges, blastula larvae swim to a new location, attach to the seabed, and develop into a new sponge.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] In most other groups, the blastula undergoes more complicated rearrangement.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] It first invaginates to form a gastrula with a digestive chamber and two separate germ layers, an external ectoderm and an internal endoderm.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] In most cases, a third germ layer, the mesoderm, also develops between them.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] These germ layers then differentiate to form tissues and organs.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Repeated instances of mating with a close relative during sexual reproduction generally leads to inbreeding depression within a population due to the increased prevalence of harmful recessive traits.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Animals have evolved numerous mechanisms for avoiding close inbreeding.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Some animals are capable of asexual reproduction, which often results in a genetic clone of the parent.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] This may take place through fragmentation; budding, such as in *Hydra* and other cnidarians; or parthenogenesis, where fertile eggs are produced without mating, such as in aphids.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Animals are categorised into ecological groups depending on their trophic levels and how they consume organic material.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Such groupings include carnivores (further divided into subcategories such as piscivores, insectivores, ovivores, etc.), herbivores (subcategorised into folivores, graminivores, frugivores, granivores, nectarivores, algivores, etc.), omnivores, fungivores, scavengers/detritivores, and parasites.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Interactions between animals of each biome form complex food webs within that ecosystem.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] In carnivorous or omnivorous species, predation is a consumer–resource interaction where the predator feeds on another organism, its prey, who often evolves anti-predator adaptations to avoid being fed upon.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Selective pressures imposed on one another lead to an evolutionary arms race between predator and prey, resulting in various antagonistic/competitive coevolutions.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Almost all multicellular predators are animals.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Some consumers use multiple methods; for example, in parasitoid wasps, the larvae feed on the hosts' living tissues, killing them in the process, but the adults primarily consume nectar from flowers.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Other animals may have very specific feeding behaviours, such as hawksbill sea turtles which mainly eat sponges.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Most animals rely on biomass and bioenergy produced by plants and phytoplanktons (collectively called producers) through photosynthesis.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Herbivores, as primary consumers, eat the plant material directly to digest and absorb the nutrients, while carnivores and other animals on higher trophic levels indirectly acquire the nutrients by eating the herbivores or other animals that have eaten the herbivores.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Animals oxidise carbohydrates, lipids, proteins and other biomolecules in cellular respiration, which allows the animal to grow and to sustain basal metabolism and fuel other biological processes such as locomotion.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Some benthic animals living close to hydrothermal vents and cold seeps on the dark sea floor consume organic matter produced through chemosynthesis (via oxidising inorganic compounds such as hydrogen sulfide) by archaea and bacteria.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Animals originated in the ocean; all extant animal phyla, except for Micrognathozoa and Onychophora, feature at least some marine species.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] However, several lineages of arthropods begun to colonise land around the same time as land plants, between 510 and 471 million years ago, during the Late Cambrian or Early Ordovician periods.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Vertebrates such as the lobe-finned fish *Tiktaalik* started to move on to land in the late Devonian, about 375 million years ago.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Other notable animal groups that colonized land environments are Mollusca, Platyhelmintha, Annelida, Tardigrada, Onychophora, Rotifera, Nematoda.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Animals occupy virtually all of earth's habitats and microhabitats, with faunas adapted to salt water, hydrothermal vents, fresh water, hot springs, swamps, forests, pastures, deserts, air, and the interiors of other organisms.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Animals are however not particularly heat tolerant; very few of them can survive at constant temperatures above 50 °C (122 °F) or in the most extreme cold deserts of continental Antarctica.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The collective global geomorphic influence of animals on the processes shaping the Earth's surface remains largely understudied, with most studies limited to individual species and well-known exemplars.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The blue whale (*Balaenoptera musculus*) is the largest animal that has ever lived, weighing up to 190 tonnes and measuring up to 33.6 metres (110 ft) long.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The largest extant terrestrial animal is the African bush elephant (*Loxodonta africana*), weighing up to 12.25 tonnes and measuring up to 10.67 metres (35.0 ft) long.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The largest terrestrial animals that ever lived were titanosaur sauropod dinosaurs such as *Argentinosaurus*, which may have weighed as much as 73 tonnes, and *Supersaurus* which may have reached 39 metres.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Several animals are microscopic; some Myxozoa (obligate parasites within the Cnidaria) never grow larger than 20 μm, and one of the smallest species (*Myxobolus shekel*) is no more than 8.5 μm when fully grown.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The following table lists estimated numbers of described extant species for the major animal phyla, along with their principal habitats (terrestrial, fresh water, and marine), and free-living or parasitic ways of life.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Species estimates shown here are based on numbers described scientifically; much larger estimates have been calculated based on various means of prediction, and these can vary wildly.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] For instance, around 25,000–27,000 species of nematodes have been described, while published estimates of the total number of nematode species include 10,000–20,000; 500,000; 10 million; and 100 million.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Using patterns within the taxonomic hierarchy, the total number of animal species—including those not yet described—was calculated to be about 7.77 million in 2011.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Evidence of animals is found as long ago as the Cryogenian period.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] 24-Isopropylcholestane (24-ipc) has been found in rocks from roughly 650 million years ago; it is only produced by sponges and pelagophyte algae.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Its likely origin is from sponges based on molecular clock estimates for the origin of 24-ipc production in both groups.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Analyses of pelagophyte algae consistently recover a Phanerozoic origin, while analyses of sponges recover a Neoproterozoic origin, consistent with the appearance of 24-ipc in the fossil record.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The first body fossils of animals appear in the Ediacaran, represented by forms such as *Charnia* and *Spriggina*.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] It had long been doubted whether these fossils truly represented animals, but the discovery of the animal lipid cholesterol in fossils of *Dickinsonia* establishes their nature.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Animals are thought to have originated under low-oxygen conditions, suggesting that they were capable of living entirely by anaerobic respiration, but as they became specialised for aerobic metabolism they became fully dependent on oxygen in their environments.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Many animal phyla first appear in the fossil record during the Cambrian explosion, starting about 539 million years ago, in beds such as the Burgess Shale.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Extant phyla in these rocks include molluscs, brachiopods, onychophorans, tardigrades, arthropods, echinoderms and hemichordates, along with numerous now-extinct forms such as the predatory *Anomalocaris*.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The apparent suddenness of the event may however be an artefact of the fossil record, rather than showing that all these animals appeared simultaneously.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] That view is supported by the discovery of *Auroralumina attenboroughii*, the earliest known Ediacaran crown-group cnidarian (557–562 mya, some 20 million years before the Cambrian explosion) from Charnwood Forest, England.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] It is thought to be one of the earliest predators, catching small prey with its nematocysts as modern cnidarians do.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Some palaeontologists have suggested that animals appeared much earlier than the Cambrian explosion, possibly as early as 1 billion years ago.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Early fossils that might represent animals appear for example in the 665-million-year-old rocks of the Trezona Formation of South Australia.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] These fossils are interpreted as most probably being early sponges.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Trace fossils such as tracks and burrows found in the Tonian period (from 1 gya) may indicate the presence of triploblastic worm-like animals, roughly as large (about 5 mm wide) and complex as earthworms.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] However, similar tracks are produced by the giant single-celled protist *Gromia sphaerica*, so the Tonian trace fossils may not indicate early animal evolution.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Around the same time, the layered mats of microorganisms called stromatolites decreased in diversity, perhaps due to grazing by newly evolved animals.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Objects such as sediment-filled tubes that resemble trace fossils of the burrows of wormlike animals have been found in 1.2 gya rocks in North America, in 1.5 gya rocks in Australia and North America, and in 1.7 gya rocks in Australia.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Their interpretation as having an animal origin is disputed, as they might be water-escape or other structures.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Animals are monophyletic, meaning they are derived from a common ancestor.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Animals are the sister group to the choanoflagellates, with which they form the Choanozoa.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Ros-Rocher and colleagues (2021) trace the origins of animals to unicellular ancestors, providing the external phylogeny shown in the cladogram.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Uncertainty of relationships is indicated with dashed lines.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The animal clade had certainly originated by 650 mya, and may have come into being as much as 800 mya, based on molecular clock evidence for different phyla.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The relationships at the base of the animal tree have been debated.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Other than Ctenophora, the Bilateria and Cnidaria are the only groups with symmetry, and other evidence shows they are closely related.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] In addition to sponges, Placozoa has no symmetry and was often considered a "missing link" between protists and multicellular animals.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The presence of hox genes in Placozoa shows that they were once more complex.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The Porifera (sponges) have long been assumed to be sister to the rest of the animals, but there is evidence that the Ctenophora may be in that position.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Molecular phylogenetics has supported both the sponge-sister and ctenophore-sister hypotheses.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Sponges are physically very distinct from other animals, and were long thought to have diverged first, representing the oldest animal phylum and forming a sister clade to all other animals.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Despite their morphological dissimilarity with all other animals, genetic evidence suggests sponges may be more closely related to other animals than the comb jellies are.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Sponges lack the complex organisation found in most other animal phyla; their cells are differentiated, but in most cases not organised into distinct tissues, unlike all other animals.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Sponges are almost entirely sessile in their adult stage.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Sponges lack a digestive, circulatory, respiratory, or excretory system.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Instead, they rely on the flow of water through their bodies to perform these functions.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Many have adapted a hollow structure to facilitate the flow of water through their bodies.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] They typically feed by drawing in water through pores, filtering out small particles of food.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] They absorb oxygen dissolved in water, and they release carbon dioxide and nitrogenous waste into water that flows through them.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Sponges can reproduce sexually and asexually.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Asexual reproduction happens through a variety of mechanisms including by fragmentation, where a piece of the sponge splits off and reestablishes somewhere else.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] For sexual reproduction, most sponges are hermaphrodites, they produce both egg and sperm cells.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Comb jellies, members of Ctenophora, are radially symmetric and have digestive chambers with a single opening, which serves as both mouth and anus.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Ctenophora have distinct tissues, but these are not organised into discrete organs.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] They move using large arrays of cilia, called swimming plates.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] They have are unique in having colloblasts, structures on their tentacles that help them catch prey.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] They have nerve cells, but lack a brain or central nervous system.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Instead their nerves are arranged into a nerve net.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Their nerves are very different from those of other animals, and evidence suggests that their nerves developed independently of the nerves of other animals.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Like Ctenophora, Cnidaria are radially symmetric and have digestive chambers with a single opening, which serves as both mouth and anus.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] They also have distinct tissues that are not organised into discrete organs.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Members of the group Anthozoa, such as sea anemones, coral, and sea pens only are sessile polyps.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Most members of Medusozoa, including jellyfish and most hydrozoans, have a polyp form as well, but also have a motile medusae stage.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The medusae stage are commonly known as jellyfish.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Cnidaria are diploblastic, having only two main germ layers, ectoderm and endoderm.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The tiny placozoans have no permanent digestive chamber and no symmetry; they superficially resemble amoebae.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Their phylogeny is poorly defined, and under active research.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The remaining animals, the great majority—comprising some 29 phyla and over a million species—form the Bilateria clade, which have a bilaterally symmetric body plan.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The Bilateria are triploblastic, with three well-developed germ layers, and their tissues form distinct organs.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The digestive chamber has two openings, a mouth and an anus, and in the Nephrozoa there is an internal body cavity, a coelom or pseudocoelom.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] These animals have a head end (anterior) and a tail end (posterior), a back (dorsal) surface and a belly (ventral) surface, and a left and a right side.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] A modern consensus phylogenetic tree for the Bilateria is shown below.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Having a front end means that this part of the body encounters stimuli, such as food, favouring cephalisation, the development of a head with sense organs and a mouth.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Many bilaterians have a combination of circular muscles that constrict the body, making it longer, and an opposing set of longitudinal muscles, that shorten the body; these enable soft-bodied animals with a hydrostatic skeleton to move by peristalsis.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] They also have a gut that extends through the basically cylindrical body from mouth to anus.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Many bilaterian phyla have primary larvae which swim with cilia and have an apical organ containing sensory cells.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] However, over evolutionary time, descendant spaces have evolved which have lost one or more of each of these characteristics.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] For example, adult echinoderms are radially symmetric (unlike their larvae), while some parasitic worms have extremely simplified body structures.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Genetic studies have considerably changed zoologists' understanding of the relationships within the Bilateria.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Most appear to belong to two major lineages, the protostomes and the deuterostomes.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] It is often suggested that the basalmost bilaterians are the Xenacoelomorpha, with all other bilaterians belonging to the subclade Nephrozoa.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] However, this suggestion has been contested, with other studies finding that xenacoelomorphs are more closely related to Ambulacraria than to other bilaterians.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Protostomes and deuterostomes differ in several ways.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Early in development, deuterostome embryos undergo radial cleavage during cell division, while many protostomes (the Spiralia) undergo spiral cleavage.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Animals from both groups possess a complete digestive tract, but in protostomes the first opening of the embryonic gut develops into the mouth, and the anus forms secondarily.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] In deuterostomes, the anus forms first while the mouth develops secondarily.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Most protostomes have schizocoelous development, where cells simply fill in the interior of the gastrula to form the mesoderm.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] In deuterostomes, the mesoderm forms by enterocoelic pouching, through invagination of the endoderm.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The main deuterostome taxa are the Ambulacraria and the Chordata.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Ambulacraria are exclusively marine and include acorn worms, starfish, sea urchins, and sea cucumbers.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The chordates are dominated by the vertebrates (animals with backbones), which consist of fishes, amphibians, reptiles, birds, and mammals.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The protostomes include the Ecdysozoa, named after their shared trait of ecdysis, growth by moulting, Among the largest ecdysozoan phyla are the arthropods and the nematodes.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The rest of the protostomes are in the Spiralia, named for their pattern of developing by spiral cleavage in the early embryo.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Major spiralian phyla include the annelids and molluscs.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] In the classical era, Aristotle divided animals, based on his own observations, into those with blood (roughly, the vertebrates) and those without.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] In 1758, Carl Linnaeus created the first hierarchical classification in his *Systema Naturae*.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] In his original scheme, the animals were one of three kingdoms, divided into the classes of Vermes, Insecta, Pisces, Amphibia, Aves, and Mammalia.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Since then, the last four have all been subsumed into a single phylum, the Chordata, while his Insecta (which included the crustaceans and arachnids) and Vermes have been renamed or broken up.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The process was begun in 1793 by Jean-Baptiste de Lamarck, who called the Vermes *une espèce de chaos* ('a chaotic mess') and split the group into three new phyla: worms, echinoderms, and polyps (which contained corals and jellyfish).
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] By 1809, in his *Philosophie Zoologique*, Lamarck had created nine phyla apart from vertebrates (where he still had four phyla: mammals, birds, reptiles, and fish) and molluscs, namely cirripedes, annelids, crustaceans, arachnids, insects, worms, radiates, polyps, and infusorians.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] This division into four was followed by the embryologist Karl Ernst von Baer in 1828, the zoologist Louis Agassiz in 1857, and the comparative anatomist Richard Owen in 1860.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] In 1874, Ernst Haeckel divided the animal kingdom into two subkingdoms: Metazoa (multicellular animals, with five phyla: coelenterates, echinoderms, articulates, molluscs, and vertebrates) and Protozoa (single-celled animals), including a sixth animal phylum, sponges.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The protozoa were later moved to the former kingdom Protista, leaving only the Metazoa as a synonym of Animalia.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The human population exploits a large number of other animal species for food, both of domesticated livestock species in animal husbandry and, mainly at sea, by hunting wild species.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Marine fish of many species are caught commercially for food.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] A smaller number of species are farmed commercially.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Humans and their livestock make up more than 90% of the biomass of all terrestrial vertebrates, and almost as much as all insects combined.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Invertebrates including cephalopods, crustaceans, insects—principally bees and silkworms—and bivalve or gastropod molluscs are hunted or farmed for food, fibres.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Chickens, cattle, sheep, pigs, and other animals are raised as livestock for meat across the world.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Animal fibres such as wool and silk are used to make textiles, while animal sinews have been used as lashings and bindings, and leather is widely used to make shoes and other items.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Animals have been hunted and farmed for their fur to make items such as coats and hats.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Dyestuffs including carmine (cochineal), shellac, and kermes have been made from the bodies of insects.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Working animals including cattle and horses have been used for work and transport from the first days of agriculture.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Animals such as the fruit fly *Drosophila melanogaster* serve a major role in science as experimental models.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Animals have been used to create vaccines since their discovery in the 18th century.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Some medicines such as the cancer drug trabectedin are based on toxins or other molecules of animal origin.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] People have used hunting dogs to help chase down and retrieve animals, and birds of prey to catch birds and mammals, while tethered cormorants have been used to catch fish.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Poison dart frogs have been used to poison the tips of blowpipe darts.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] A wide variety of animals are kept as pets, from invertebrates such as tarantulas, octopuses, and praying mantises, reptiles such as snakes and chameleons, and birds including canaries, parakeets, and parrots all finding a place.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] However, the most kept pet species are mammals, namely dogs, cats, and rabbits.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] There is a tension between the role of animals as companions to humans, and their existence as individuals with rights of their own.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] A wide variety of terrestrial and aquatic animals are hunted for sport.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The signs of the Western and Chinese zodiacs are based on animals.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] In China and Japan, the butterfly has been seen as the personification of a person's soul, and in classical representation the butterfly is also the symbol of the soul.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Animals have been the subjects of art from the earliest times, both historical, as in ancient Egypt, and prehistoric, as in the cave paintings at Lascaux.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Major animal paintings include Albrecht Dürer's 1515 *The Rhinoceros*, and George Stubbs's c.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Insects, birds and mammals play roles in literature and film, such as in giant bug movies.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Animals including insects and mammals feature in mythology and religion.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] The scarab beetle was sacred in ancient Egypt, and the cow is sacred in Hinduism.
[src:bornean-orangutan/animal] Among other mammals, deer, horses, lions, bats, bears, and wolves are the subjects of myths and worship.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape-cognition-and-conservation-initiative] Ape Cognition and Conservation Initiative is situated on 230 acres and houses a family of six bonobos, named Elikya, Maisha, Nyota, Teco, Clara, and Mali.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape-cognition-and-conservation-initiative] Three of the bonobos learned important elements of human culture during their crucial first year of life.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape-cognition-and-conservation-initiative] As a youngster, Kanzi acquired language competency by simply watching humans attempt to teach language to Matata, the wild-caught grandmother of the family.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape-cognition-and-conservation-initiative] Nyota is the first ape reared both by humans and a language-competent ape mother.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape-cognition-and-conservation-initiative] The youngest, Teco, provides a unique look into the epigenetic effects of language acquisition.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape-cognition-and-conservation-initiative] All three of these bonobos communicate with humans using a collection of over 400 "lexigram" symbols printed on paper or appearing on computer touch screens.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape-cognition-and-conservation-initiative] It has been repeatedly claimed that these bonobos can think, make plans and understand simple spoken English.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape-cognition-and-conservation-initiative] Kanzi was filmed making music, building a fire, and crafting simple stone tools.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape-cognition-and-conservation-initiative] More than 400 scientific papers and many books document the capabilities of the bonobos, and films portraying their achievements have been broadcast worldwide.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape-cognition-and-conservation-initiative] Television coverage includes features with Oprah, Anderson Cooper, *60 Minutes* (in Australia), BBC, Paul McCartney and Peter Gabriel.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Except for gorillas and humans, hominoids are agile climbers of trees.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Apes eat a variety of plants and animals.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Plants, which can include fruits, leaves, stalks, roots, nuts, and seeds, make up the bulk of their diet.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Human diets are sometimes substantially different from that of other hominoids, due in part to the development of technology and a wide range of habitation.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] All extant non-human hominoids are rare and threatened with extinction.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] The main threat is habitat loss, though some populations are further imperiled by hunting.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] The great apes of Africa are also facing threat from the Ebola virus.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] "Ape", from Old English *apa*, is a word of uncertain origin.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] The term has a history of rather imprecise usage—and of comedic or punning usage in the vernacular.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Its earliest meaning was generally of any non-human anthropoid primate, as is still the case for its cognates in other Germanic languages.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Later, after the term "monkey" had been introduced into English, "ape" was specialized to refer to a tailless (therefore exceptionally human-like) primate.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Thus, the term "ape" obtained two different meanings, as shown in the 1911 *Encyclopædia Britannica* entry: it could be used as a synonym for "monkey" and it could denote the tailless human-like primate in particular.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Some, or recently all, hominoids are also called "apes", but the term is used broadly and has several different senses within both popular and scientific settings.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] "Ape" has been used as a synonym for "monkey" or for naming any primate with a human-like appearance, particularly those without a tail.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Biologists have traditionally used the term "ape" to mean a member of the superfamily Hominoidea *other than* humans, but more recently to mean *all* members of Hominoidea.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] So "ape"—not to be confused with "great ape"—now becomes another word for **hominoid** *including* humans.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] The taxonomic term *hominoid* is derived from, and intended as encompassing, the *hominids,* the family of great apes.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Both terms were introduced by John Edward Gray (1825).
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] The term *hominins* is also due to Gray (1824), intended as including the human lineage (see also Hominidae#Terminology, Human taxonomy).
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] The distinction between apes and monkeys is complicated by the traditional paraphyly of monkeys: Apes emerged as a sister group of Old World Monkeys in the catarrhines, which are a sister group of New World Monkeys.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Therefore, cladistically, apes, catarrhines and related contemporary extinct groups such as Parapithecidae are monkeys as well, for any consistent definition of "monkey".
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] "Old World monkey" may also legitimately be taken to be meant to include all the catarrhines, including apes and extinct species such as *Aegyptopithecus*, in which case the apes, Cercopithecoidea and *Aegyptopithecus* emerged within the Old World monkeys.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] The primates called "apes" today became known to Europeans after the 18th century.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] As zoological knowledge developed, it became clear that taillessness occurred in a number of different and otherwise distantly related species.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Sir Wilfrid Le Gros Clark was one of those primatologists who developed the idea that there were trends in primate evolution and that the extant members of the order could be arranged in an "ascending series", leading from "monkeys" to "apes" to humans.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Within this tradition "ape" came to refer to all members of the superfamily Hominoidea except humans.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] As such, this use of "apes" represented a paraphyletic grouping, meaning that, even though all species of apes were descended from a common ancestor, this grouping did *not* include all the descendant species, because humans were excluded from being among the apes.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Traditionally, the English-language vernacular name "apes" does not include humans, but phylogenetically, humans (*Homo*) form part of the family Hominidae within Hominoidea.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Modern taxonomy aims for the use of monophyletic groups for taxonomic classification; Some literature may now use the common name "ape" to mean all members of the superfamily Hominoidea, including humans.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] For example, in his 2005 book, Benton wrote "The apes, Hominoidea, today include the gibbons and orang-utan ... the gorilla and chimpanzee ... and humans".
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Modern biologists and primatologists refer to apes that are not human as "non-human" apes.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Scientists broadly, other than paleoanthropologists, may use the term "hominin" to identify the human clade, replacing the term "hominid".
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] See below, History of hominoid taxonomy, for a discussion of changes in scientific classification and terminology regarding hominoids.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Although the hominoid fossil record is still incomplete and fragmentary, there is now enough evidence to provide an outline of the evolutionary history of humans.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Previously, the divergence between humans and other extant hominoids was thought to have occurred 15 to 20 million years ago, and several species of that time period, such as *Ramapithecus*, were once thought to be hominins and possible ancestors of humans.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Genetic analysis combined with fossil evidence indicates that hominoids diverged from the Old World monkeys about 25 million years ago (mya), near the Oligocene–Miocene boundary.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] The gibbons split from the rest about 18 mya, and the hominid splits happened 14 mya (*Pongo*), 7 mya (*Gorilla*), and 3–5 mya (*Homo* & *Pan*).
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] In 2015, a new genus and species were described, *Pliobates cataloniae*, which lived 11.6 mya, and appears to predate the split between Hominidae and Hylobatidae.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] The history of hominoid taxonomy is complex and somewhat confusing.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Recent evidence has changed our understanding of the relationships between the hominoids, especially regarding the human lineage; and the traditionally used terms have become somewhat confused.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Competing approaches to methodology and terminology are found among current scientific sources.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] There has been a gradual demotion of humans from being 'special' in the taxonomy to being one branch among many.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] This recent turmoil (of history) illustrates the growing influence on all taxonomy of cladistics, the science of classifying living things strictly according to their lines of descent.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Today, there are eight extant genera of hominoids.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] They are the four genera in the family Hominidae, namely *Homo*, *Pan*, *Gorilla*, and *Pongo*; plus four genera in the family Hylobatidae (gibbons): *Hylobates*, *Hoolock*, *Nomascus* and *Symphalangus*.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] (The two subspecies of hoolock gibbons were recently moved from the genus *Bunopithecus* to the new genus *Hoolock* and re-ranked as species; a third species was described in January 2017).
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] In 1758, Carl Linnaeus, relying on second- or third-hand accounts, placed a second species in *Homo* along with *H. sapiens*: *Homo troglodytes* ("cave-dwelling man").
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Although the term "Orang Outang" is listed as a variety – *Homo sylvestris* – under this species, it is nevertheless not clear to which animal this name refers, as Linnaeus had no specimen to refer to, hence no precise description.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Linnaeus may have based *Homo troglodytes* on reports of mythical creatures, then-unidentified simians, or Asian natives dressed in animal skins.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Linnaeus named the orangutan *Simia satyrus* ("satyr monkey").
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] He placed the three genera *Homo*, *Simia* and *Lemur* in the order of Primates.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] The *troglodytes* name was used for the chimpanzee by Blumenbach in 1775, but moved to the genus *Simia*.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] The orangutan was moved to the genus *Pongo* in 1799 by Lacépède.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Linnaeus's inclusion of humans in the primates with monkeys and apes was troubling for people who denied a close relationship between humans and the rest of the animal kingdom.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Linnaeus's Lutheran archbishop had accused him of "impiety".
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Accordingly, Johann Friedrich Blumenbach in the first edition of his *Manual of Natural History* (1779), proposed that the primates be divided into the Quadrumana (four-handed, i.e. apes and monkeys) and Bimana (two-handed, i.e. humans).
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] This distinction was taken up by other naturalists, most notably Georges Cuvier.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Some elevated the distinction to the level of order.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] However, the many affinities between humans and other primates – and especially the "great apes" – made it clear that the distinction made no scientific sense.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] The lesser apes are the gibbon family, Hylobatidae, of sixteen species; all are native to Asia.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Their major differentiating characteristic is their long arms, which they use to brachiate through trees.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Their wrists are ball and socket joints as an evolutionary adaptation to their arboreal lifestyle.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Generally smaller than the African apes, the largest gibbon, the siamang, weighs up to 14 kg (31 lb); in comparison, the smallest "great ape", the bonobo, is 34 to 60 kg (75 to 132 lb).
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] The superfamily Hominoidea falls within the parvorder Catarrhini, which also includes the Old World monkeys of Africa and Eurasia.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Within this grouping, the two families Hylobatidae and Hominidae can be distinguished from Old World monkeys by the number of cusps on their molars; hominoids have five in the "Y-5" molar pattern, whereas Old World monkeys have only four in a bilophodont pattern.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] These are anatomical adaptations, first, to vertical hanging and swinging locomotion (brachiation) and, later, to developing balance in a bipedal pose.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Note there are primates in other families that also lack tails, and at least one, the pig-tailed langur, is known to walk significant distances bipedally.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] The front of the ape skull is characterised by its sinuses, fusion of the frontal bone, and by post-orbital constriction.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Cladistically, apes, catarrhines, and extinct species such as Aegyptopithecus and Parapithecidaea, are monkeys, so one can only specify ape features not present in other monkeys.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Unlike most monkeys, apes do not possess a tail.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Monkeys are more likely to be in trees and use their tails for balance.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] While the great apes are considerably larger than monkeys, gibbons (lesser apes) are smaller than some monkeys.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Apes are considered to be more intelligent than monkeys, which are considered to have more primitive brains.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] The enzyme urate oxidase has become inactive in all apes, its function having been lost in two primate lineages during the middle Miocene; first in the common ancestors of Hominidae, and later in the common ancestor of Hylobatidae.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] It has been hypothesized that in both incidents it was a mutation that occurred in apes living in Europe when the climate was getting colder, leading to starvation during winter.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] The mutation changed the biochemistry of the apes and made it easier to accumulate fat, which allowed the animals to survive longer periods of starvation.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] When they migrated to Asia and Africa, this genetic trait remained.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Major studies of behaviour in the field were completed on the three better-known "great apes", for example by Jane Goodall, Dian Fossey and Birutė Galdikas.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Their diets also vary; gorillas are foliovores, while the others are all primarily frugivores, although the common chimpanzee hunts for meat.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Foraging behaviour is correspondingly variable.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] In November 2023, scientists reported, for the first time, evidence that groups of primates, including apes, and, particularly bonobos, are capable of cooperating with each other.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Apart from humans and gorillas, apes eat a predominantly frugivorous diet, mostly fruit, but supplemented with a variety of other foods.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Gorillas are predominantly folivorous, eating mostly stalks, shoots, roots and leaves with some fruit and other foods.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Non-human apes usually eat a small amount of raw animal foods such as insects or eggs.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] In the case of humans, migration and the invention of hunting tools and cooking has led to an even wider variety of foods and diets, with many human diets including large amounts of cooked tubers (roots) or legumes.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Other food production and processing methods including animal husbandry and industrial refining and processing have further changed human diets.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Humans and other apes occasionally eat other primates.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Some of these primates are now close to extinction with habitat loss being the underlying cause.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] All the non-human hominoids are generally thought of as highly intelligent, and scientific study has broadly confirmed that they perform very well on a wide range of cognitive tests—though there is relatively little data on gibbon cognition.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] The early studies by Wolfgang Köhler demonstrated exceptional problem-solving abilities in chimpanzees, which Köhler attributed to insight.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] The use of tools has been repeatedly demonstrated; more recently, the manufacture of tools has been documented, both in the wild and in laboratory tests.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Imitation is much more easily demonstrated in "great apes" than in other primate species.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Almost all the studies in animal language acquisition have been done with "great apes", and though there is continuing dispute as to whether they demonstrate real language abilities, there is no doubt that they involve significant feats of learning.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Chimpanzees in different parts of Africa have developed tools that are used in food acquisition, demonstrating a form of animal culture.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] All non-human hominoids are rare and threatened with extinction.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] The eastern hoolock gibbon is the least threatened, only being vulnerable to extinction.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Five gibbon species are critically endangered, as are all species of orangutan and gorilla.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] The remaining species of gibbon, the bonobo, and all four subspecies of chimpanzees are endangered.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] The chief threat to most of the endangered species is loss of tropical rainforest habitat, though some populations are further imperiled by hunting for bushmeat.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Currently considered to be the greatest threat to survival of African apes, Ebola infection is responsible for the death of at least one third of all gorillas and chimpanzees since 1990.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] All the species of great apes in Africa are considered endangered.
[src:bornean-orangutan/ape] Hunting, logging, agricultural expansion and mining are among the main threats.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Some animals are exclusively arboreal in habitat, such as tree snails.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Arboreal habitats pose numerous mechanical challenges to animals moving in them, which have been solved in diverse ways.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] These challenges include moving on narrow branches, moving up and down inclines, balancing, crossing gaps, and dealing with obstructions.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Moving along narrow surfaces, such as a branch of a tree, can create special difficulties for animals who are not adapted to deal with balancing on small diameter substrates.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] During locomotion on the ground, the location of the center of mass may swing from side to side.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] But during arboreal locomotion, this would result in the center of mass moving beyond the edge of the branch, resulting in a tendency to topple over and fall.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Not only do some arboreal animals have to be able to move on branches of varying diameter, but they also have to eat on these branches, resulting in the need for the ability to balance while using their hands to feed themselves.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] This resulted in various types of grasping such as pedal grasping in order to clamp themselves onto small branches for better balance.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Branches are frequently oriented at an angle to gravity in arboreal habitats, including being vertical, which poses special problems.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] As an animal moves up an inclined branch, it must fight the force of gravity to raise its body, making the movement more difficult.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] To get past this difficulty, many animals have to grasp the substrate with all four limbs and increase the frequency of their gait sequence.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Conversely, as the animal descends, it must also fight gravity to control its descent and prevent falling.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Descent can be particularly problematic for many animals, and highly arboreal species often have specialized methods for controlling their descent.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] One way animals prevent falling while descending is to increase the amount of contact their limbs are making with the substrate to increase friction and braking power.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Due to the height of many branches and the potentially disastrous consequences of a fall, balance is of primary importance to arboreal animals.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] On horizontal and gently sloped branches, the primary problem is tipping to the side due to the narrow base of support.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] The narrower the branch, the greater the difficulty in balancing a given animal faces.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] On steep and vertical branches, tipping becomes less of an issue, and pitching backwards or slipping downwards becomes the most likely failure.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] In this case, large-diameter branches pose a greater challenge since the animal cannot place its forelimbs closer to the center of the branch than its hindlimbs.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Some arboreal animals need to be able to move from tree to tree in order to find food and shelter.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] To be able to get from tree to tree, animals have evolved various adaptations.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] In some areas trees are close together and can be crossed by simple brachiation.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] In other areas, trees are not close together and animals need to have specific adaptations to jump far distances or glide.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Arboreal habitats often contain many obstructions, both in the form of branches emerging from the one being moved on and other branches impinging on the space the animal needs to move through.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] These obstructions may impede locomotion, or may be used as additional contact points to enhance it.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] While obstructions tend to impede limbed animals, they benefit snakes by providing anchor points.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Arboreal organisms display many specializations for dealing with the mechanical challenges of moving through their habitats.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Arboreal animals frequently have elongated limbs that help them cross gaps, reach fruit or other resources, test the firmness of support ahead, and in some cases, to brachiate.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] However, some species of lizard have reduced limb size that helps them avoid limb movement being obstructed by impinging branches.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Many arboreal species, such as howler monkeys, green tree pythons, emerald tree boas, chameleons, silky anteaters, spider monkeys, and possums, use prehensile tails to grasp branches.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] In the spider monkey and crested gecko, the tip of the tail has either a bare patch or adhesive pad, which provides increased friction.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Various organisms use claws to negotiate rough surfaces such as rockfaces or corky substrates and re-orient the direction of the force the animal applies.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] This allows lizards such as Agamas and Cordylidae to inhabit cliffs, and squirrels to climb tree trunks that are so large as to be essentially flat.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] However, claws can interfere with an animal's ability to grasp very small branches, as they may wrap too far around and prick the animal's own paw.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Adhesion is an alternative to claws, which works best on smooth surfaces.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Wet adhesion is common in tree frogs and arboreal salamanders, and functions either by suction or by capillary adhesion.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Dry adhesion is best typified by the specialized toes of geckos, which use van der Waals forces to adhere to many substrates, even glass.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] In some species of geckoes, such as in the genus Lygodactylus, the reliance on van der Waals forces is supplemented by a patch of specialised scales under the tip of the tail; a tail regenerated after defensive autotomy however, lacks that adhesive tip.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Frictional gripping is used by primates, relying upon hairless fingertips.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Squeezing the branch between the fingertips generates a frictional force that holds the animal's hand to the branch.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] However, this type of grip depends upon the angle of the frictional force; thus upon the diameter of the branch, with larger branches resulting in reduced gripping ability.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Animals other than primates that use gripping in climbing include the chameleon, which has mitten-like grasping feet, and many birds that grip branches in perching or moving about.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] To control descent, especially down large diameter branches, some arboreal animals such as squirrels have evolved highly mobile ankle joints that permit rotating the foot into a 'reversed' posture.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] This allows the claws to hook into the rough surface of the bark, opposing the force of gravity.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Many arboreal species lower their center of mass to reduce pitching and toppling movement when climbing.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] This may be accomplished by postural changes, altered body proportions, or smaller size.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Small size provides many advantages to arboreal species: such as increasing the relative size of branches to the animal, lower center of mass, increased stability, lower mass (allowing movement on smaller branches), and the ability to move through more cluttered habitat.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Size relating to weight affects gliding animals such as the reduced weight per snout-vent length for "flying" frogs.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Some species of primates, bats, and all species of sloths achieve passive stability by hanging beneath the branch.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Both pitching and tipping become irrelevant, as the only method of failure would be losing their grip.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Arboreal species have behaviors specialized for moving in their habitats, most prominently in terms of posture and gait.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Specifically, arboreal mammals take longer steps, extend their limbs further forwards and backwards during a step, adopt a more 'crouched' posture to lower their center of mass, and use a diagonal sequence gait.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Brachiation is a specialized form of arboreal locomotion, used by primates to move very rapidly while hanging beneath branches.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Arguably the epitome of arboreal locomotion, it involves swinging with the arms from one handhold to another.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Only a few species are brachiators, and all of these are primates; it is a major means of locomotion among spider monkeys and gibbons, and is occasionally used by female orangutans.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Gibbons are the experts of this mode of locomotion, swinging from branch to branch distances of up to 15 m (50 ft), and traveling at speeds of as much as 56 km/h (35 mph).
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] To bridge gaps between trees, many animals such as the flying squirrel have adapted membranes, such as patagia for gliding flight.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Some animals can slow their descent in the air using a method known as parachuting, such as *Rhacophorus* (a "flying frog" species) that has adapted toe membranes allowing it to fall more slowly after leaping from trees.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] Many species of snake are highly arboreal, and some have evolved specialized musculature for this habitat.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] While moving in arboreal habitats, snakes move slowly along bare branches using a specialized form of concertina locomotion, but when secondary branches emerge from the branch being moved on, snakes use lateral undulation, a much faster mode.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] As a result, snakes perform best on small perches in cluttered environments, while limbed organisms seem to do best on large perches in uncluttered environments.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] The earliest known climbing tetrapod is the varanopid amniote *Eoscansor* from the Late Carboniferous (Pennsylvanian) of North America which is clearly specialised with adaptations for grasping, likely onto tree trunks.
[src:bornean-orangutan/arboreal-locomotion] *Suminia*, a anomodont synapsid from Russia dating to the Late Permian, about 260 million years ago, was also likely a specialised climber.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The **Bornean orangutan** (***Pongo pygmaeus***) is an orangutan species endemic to the island of Borneo.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] It belongs to the only genus of great apes native to Asia and is the largest of the three *Pongo* species.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] It has a coarse, reddish coat and up to 1.5 m (4 ft 11 in) long arms.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] It is sexually dimorphic — males are larger than females and develop large cheek pads (flanges).
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The Bornean orangutan inhabits Borneo lowland rain forests and Borneo montane rain forests up to an elevation of 1,500 m (4,900 ft).
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Its diet includes fruits, seeds, flowers, bird eggs, sap and vines.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] It is highly intelligent, displaying tool use and distinct cultural patterns.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] It is listed as Critically Endangered, with deforestation, palm oil plantations, and hunting posing a serious threat to its survival.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Bornean orangutans diverged from Tapanuli orangutans about 674,000 years ago.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The Bornean orangutan and the Sumatran orangutan diverged about 400,000 years ago, with a continued low level of gene flow between them since then.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The Bornean orangutan and the Sumatran orangutan were considered merely subspecies until 1996; they were elevated to species following sequencing of their mitochondrial DNA.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Tapanuli orangutan was identified as a distinct species in 2017.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] There is some uncertainty about this, however.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The population currently listed as *P. p. wurmbii* may be closer to the Sumatran orangutan (*P. abelii*) than to the Bornean orangutan.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] If this is confirmed, *P. abelii* would be a subspecies of *P. wurmbii* (Tiedeman, 1808).
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Bradon-Jones *et al.* considered *P. morio* to be a synonym of *P. pygmaeus*, and the population found in East Kalimantan and Sabah to be a potentially unnamed separate taxon.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] In early October 2014, researchers from domestic and foreign countries found about 50 orangutans in several groups in South Kalimantan Province, although previously there is no record that the province has orangutans.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] As a member of the family Hominidae, Bornean orangutans are one of the closest extant relatives to *Homo sapiens*.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] This species was originally discovered by native Malaysians.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] There are several mentions of orangutans in their folklore.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] However, this species was originally named and described by the notable zoologist Carl Linnaeus in 1799.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Its original name was *Simia satyrus*, meaning "satyr monkey", but was changed when scientists discovered that not all orangutans are one species.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The holotype of this organism is located in the British Museum in London.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The genus name *Pongo* is derived from the Bantu word **mpongo** used to indicate a large primate.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] It was originally used to describe chimpanzees in Western African dialects.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The species name *pygmaeus* is derived from the Greek word "pygmy" meaning dwarf.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The Bornean orangutan is the third-largest ape after the western gorilla, and the largest truly arboreal (or tree-dwelling) extant ape.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Body weights broadly overlap with the considerably taller *Homo sapiens*, but the latter is considerably more variable in size.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] By comparison, the Sumatran orangutan is similar in size but, on average, is marginally lighter in weight.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] A survey of wild orangutans found that males weigh on average 75 kg (165 lb), ranging from 50 to 100 kg (110 to 220 lb), and 1.2–1.7 m (3 ft 11 in – 5 ft 7 in) long; females average 38.5 kg (85 lb), ranging from 30 to 50 kg (66 to 110 lb), and 1–1.2 m (3 ft 3 in – 3 ft 11 in) long.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] While in captivity, orangutans can grow considerably overweight, up to more than 165 kg (364 lb).
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The heaviest known male orangutan in captivity was an obese male named "Andy", who weighed 204 kg (450 lb) in 1959 when he was 13 years old.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The Bornean orangutan has a distinctive body shape with very long arms that may reach up to 1.5 metres in length.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] It has grey skin, a coarse, shaggy, reddish coat and prehensile, grasping hands and feet.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Its coat does not cover its face unlike most mammals, although Bornean orangutans do have some hair on their faces including a beard and mustache.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] It also has large, fatty cheek pads known as flanges as well as a pendulous throat sac.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Bornean orangutans are highly sexually dimorphic and have several features that differ between males and females.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Males have much larger cheek pads, or flanges, that are composed of muscle and large amounts of fat.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] In females, the flanges are mostly composed of muscle.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Males have relatively larger canines and premolars.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Males have a more pronounced beard and mustache.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The throat sac in males is also considerably larger.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] There are two body types for sexually mature males: smaller or larger.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Larger males are more dominant but smaller males still breed successfully.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] There is little sexual dimorphism at birth.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The Bornean orangutan lives in tropical rain forests in the Bornean lowlands, as well as montane rain forests in mountainous areas up to 1,500 m (4,900 ft).
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] This species lives throughout the canopy of primary and secondary forest, and moves large distances to find trees bearing fruit.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] It is found in the two Malaysian states of Sabah and Sarawak, and four of the five Indonesian Provinces of Kalimantan.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Due to habitat destruction, the species distribution is now highly patchy throughout the island, the species has become rare in the southeast of the island, as well as in the forest between the Rajang River in central Sarawak and the Padas River in western Sabah.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Its presence in Brunei is uncertain and unconfirmed.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The first complete orangutan skeleton that was discovered was in the Hoa Binh province in Vietnam and thought to be from the late Pleistocene epoch.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] It differed from modern orangutans only in that its body was proportionately smaller compared to its head.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] This fossil and others confirm that orangutans once inhabited continental Southeast Asia even though currently, Bornean orangutans are only found in Malaysia and Indonesia.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] In history, orangutans ranged throughout Southeast Asia and into southern China, as well as on the island of Java and in southern Sumatra.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] They primarily inhabit peat swamp forest, tropical heath forest, and mixed dipterocarp forest.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Bornean orangutan are more solitary than their Sumatran relatives.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Two or three orangutans with overlapping territories may interact, but only for short periods of time.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Although orangutans are not territorial, adult males will display threatening behaviors upon meeting other males, and only socialize with females to mate.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Males are considered the most solitary of the orangutans.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The Bornean orangutan has a lifespan of 35–45 years in the wild; in captivity it can live to be about 60.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Despite being arboreal, the Bornean orangutan travels on the ground more than its Sumatran counterpart.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] This may be in part because no large terrestrial predators could threaten an orangutan in Borneo.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] In Sumatra, orangutans must face predation by the fierce Sumatran tiger.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The Bornean orangutan exhibits nest-building behavior.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Nests are built for use at night or during the day.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Young orangutans learn by observing their mother's nest-building behaviour.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] This skill is practiced by juvenile orangutans.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Nests may be elaborate and involve a foundation and mattress made by intertwining leaves and branches and adding broken leafy branches.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Additional features such as shade, waterproof roof, "pillow", and "blanket", all of which are made from branches, twigs and leaves, may also be added.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Nest-building in primates is considered as an example of tool use and not animal architecture.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The Bornean orangutan diet is composed of over 400 types of food, including wild figs, durians (*Durio zibethinus* and *D. graveolens*), leaves, seeds, bird eggs, flowers, sap, vines, honey, fungi, spider webs, insects, and, to a lesser extent than the Sumatran orangutan, bark.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] It also consumes the inner shoots of plants and vines.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] It get the necessary quantities of water from both fruit and from tree holes.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Some individuals have also been seen eating dead fish on shores and even grabbing live fish out of the water with their hands.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] In some regions, orangutans occasionally eat soil to get minerals that may neutralize the toxins and acids they consume in their primarily vegetarian diets.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] On rare occasions, orangutans will prey upon other, smaller primates, such as slow lorises.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Males and females generally come together only to mate.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Subadult males try to mate with any female and are successful around half the time.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Dominant flanged males will call and advertise their position to receptive females, who prefer mating with flanged males.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Adult males will often target females with weaned infants as mating partners because the female is likely to be fertile.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Females reach sexual maturity and experience their first ovulatory cycle between about six and 11 years of age, although females with more body fat may experience this at an earlier age.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The estrous cycle lasts between 22 and 30 days and menopause has been reported in captive orangutans at about age 48.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Females tend to give birth at about 14–15 years of age.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Newborn orangutans nurse every three to four hours, and begin to take soft food from their mothers' lips by four months.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] During the first year of its life, the young clings to its mother's abdomen by entwining its fingers in and gripping her hair.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Offspring are weaned at about four years, but this could be much longer, and soon after they start their adolescent stage of exploring, but always within sight of their mother.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] During this period, they will also actively seek other young orangutans to play with and travel with.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] On average, juveniles do not become completely independent until they are about seven years of age.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The birth rate for orangutans has been decreasing largely due to a lack of sufficient nutrients as a result of habitat loss.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] A 2011 study on female orangutans in free-ranging rehabilitation programs found that individuals that were supplemented with food resources had shorter interbirth intervals, as well as a reduced age, at first birth.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The Bornean orangutan is more common than the Sumatran, with about 104,700 individuals in the wild, whereas just under 14,000 Sumatran orangutans are left in the wild.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Orangutans are becoming increasingly endangered due to habitat destruction and the bushmeat trade, and young orangutans are captured to be sold as pets, usually entailing the killing of their mothers.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The Bornean orangutan is critically endangered according to the IUCN Red List of mammals, and is listed on Appendix I of CITES.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The total number of Bornean orangutans is estimated to be less than 14% of what it was in the recent past (from around 10,000 years ago until the middle of the 20th century), and this sharp decline has occurred mostly over the past few decades due to human activities and development.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Species distribution is now highly patchy throughout Borneo; it is apparently absent or uncommon in the southeast of the island, as well as in the forest between the Rajang River in central Sarawak and the Padas River in western Sabah (including the Sultanate of Brunei).
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] A population of around 6,900 is found in Sabangau National Park, but this environment is at risk.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] This view is also supported by the United Nations Environment Programme, which stated in its 2007 report that, due to illegal logging, fire and the extensive development of palm oil plantations, orangutans are critically endangered, and if the current trend continues, they will become extinct.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] When forest is burned down to clear room for palm oil plantations, not only does the Bornean orangutan suffer from habitat loss, but several individuals have been burned and killed in fires.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Palm oil accounts for over one tenth of Indonesia's export earnings.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] It is in high demand because it is used in several packaged foods, deodorants, shampoos, soaps, candies, and baked goods.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Climate change is another threat to Bornean orangutan conservation.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The effects that human activity have had on Indonesian rainfall have made food less abundant and so Bornean orangutans are less likely to receive full nutrients so that they can be sufficiently healthy to breed.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] A November 2011 survey, based on interviews with 6,983 respondents in 687 villages across Kalimantan in 2008 to 2009, gave estimated orangutan killing rates of between 750 and 1800 in the year leading up to April 2008.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] These killing rates were higher than previously thought and confirm that the continued existence of the orangutan in Kalimantan is under serious threat.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The survey did not quantify the additional threat to the species due to habitat loss from deforestation and expanding palm-oil plantations.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The survey found that 73% of respondents knew orangutans were protected by Indonesian law.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] However, the Indonesian government rarely prosecutes or punishes perpetrators.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] In a rare prosecution in November 2011, two men were arrested for killing at least 20 orangutans and a number of long-nosed proboscis monkeys.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] They were ordered to conduct the killings by the supervisor of a palm oil plantation, to protect the crop, with a payment of $100 for a dead orangutan and $22 for a monkey.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] A number of orangutan rescue and rehabilitation projects operate in Borneo.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The Borneo Orangutan Survival Foundation (BOS) founded by Willie Smits has rescue and rehabilitation centres at Wanariset and Samboja Lestari in East Kalimantan and Nyaru Menteng, in Central Kalimantan founded and managed by Lone Drøscher Nielsen.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] BOS also works to conserve and recreate the fast-disappearing rainforest habitat of the orangutan, at Samboja Lestari and Mawas.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Orangutan Foundation International, founded by Birutė Galdikas, rescues and rehabilitates orangutans, preparing them for release back into protected areas of the Indonesian rain forest.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] In addition, it promotes the preservation of the rain forest for them.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The Sepilok Orangutan Rehabilitation Centre near Sandakan in the state of Sabah in Malaysian Borneo opened in 1964 as the first official orangutan rehabilitation project.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Orangutan Foundation, founded by Ashley Leiman, operates programmes in Central Kalimantan, Indonesian Borneo.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The Foundation rescues orphaned orangutans and enters them into their soft-release programme, allowing them to develop the skills necessary to survive in the wild.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] When old enough, orangutans are released into the protected Lamandau Wildlife Reserve.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Orangutan Foundation works to protect orangutans by focusing on habitat protection and capacity building, especially in local communities.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] A seven-year longitudinal study published in 2011 looked at whether the lifespan of zoo-housed orangutans was related to a subjective assessment of well-being, with the intent of applying such measures to assess the welfare of orangutans in captivity.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Of the subjects, 100 were Sumatran (*Pongo abelii*), 54 Bornean (*Pongo pygmaeus*) and 30 were hybrid orangutans.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] 113 zoo employees, who were highly familiar with the typical behavior of the orangutans, used a four-item questionnaire to assess their subjective well-being.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The results indicated that orangutans in higher subjective well-being were less likely to die during the follow-up period.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The study concluded that happiness was related to longer life in orangutans.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] In late 2014, Nyaru Menteng veterinarians failed to rescue the life of a female orangutan.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] An operation was performed in which 40 air-rifle pellets were removed from her body.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The orangutan was found at a palm oil plantation in Indonesian Borneo.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Orangutans and humans diverged lineages approximately 14–18 million years ago.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] About 17,000 years ago, there was a migration of the Bornean orangutans as they eventually went to Sumatra, effectively trading places with the Sumatra orangutans that were there at the time.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] These two species of orangutans have been closely related throughout their evolutionary history because they were so close in physical proximity.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Therefore, their genomes and demographic history are similar.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The two species themselves are estimated to have split about 3.5 million years ago.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Although these two species have officially diverged, it is speculated that the reason as to why they are genetically similar is because the males of each respective species tend to migrate between the two islands and breed with the females from their sister species.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] As a result, both the Bornean orangutans and the Sumatran orangutans have been studied closely as a pair, and thus much genome findings attribute evolutionary changes to this relationship.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] In addition, the Bornean orangutans, as compared to the Sumatran orangutans, have lower autosomal gene diversity.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] This is attributed to the fact that they have a much smaller population size.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Also, the Bornean orangutans have lower nucleotide diversity.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] As the Bornean orangutans and Sumatran orangutans both exist within the same genus, they exhibit similar cultural behaviors that have been found to exist amongst most orangutan populations.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The fact that orangutans tend to showcase similar cultural traditions is because they typically live in similar environments and are adept at learning from one another from their early stages of life.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] The Bornean orangutan has been linked to the fact that it has gone through a deep divergence in relation to its relatives and ancestors.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] During the Middle Pleistocene, there were low levels of gene flow, which was determined through the analysis of Y-chromosomal data.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] One reason as to why this may have occurred is because of the Sunda Shelf, which is where the island of Borneo is located.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] During this time, this event's dry climate during the Late Pleistocene attributed to a more abundant genetic exchange.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] As a result, there were many early divergences of gene pools between the Bornean orangutans, as well as the Sumatran orangutans.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Relating back to the Middle Pleistocene, the Bornean orangutan lineage went through a dramatic population decline.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] This is likely attributed to the fact that they had been isolated from their ancestral populations.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] Therefore, natural geographic barriers are attributed to be the reason as to why the Bornean orangutans were eventually isolated and ended up colonizing other regions.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] In addition, this geographic isolation also indicates that the Bornean orangutans did not undergo a severe genetic bottleneck.
[src:bornean-orangutan/bornean-orangutan] With the Borneo orangutan, selection was found to have been found through physiological adaptations – most of which has to do with being able to adapt to the ever-changing climate on the Borneo island.
